window.VERDICTS = {"airbus-a380|boeing-747":"The 747 invented the widebody and ruled for thirty-eight years; the A380 was built to dethrone it and arrived exactly as the market it was designed for evaporated. The A380 wins every dimension that can be measured — longer wings, taller, heavier, hundreds more seats — and lost the argument anyway. Point-to-point flying dissolved the hub-and-spoke logic both aircraft were built on, and the twin-engine 777 and 787 finished the pair of them off.","airbus-a320|boeing-737":"The most consequential rivalry in aviation, and the numbers are almost boringly close — a metre here, half a metre there. That is not coincidence: both are sized to the same gates, the same airbridges, the same 150-seat sweet spot. The real difference is under the skin. The A320 was fly-by-wire from 1987. The 737 is a 1967 airframe stretched, re-engined and recertified for six decades — and that constraint is precisely why the MAX's engines sit so far forward on the wing.","airbus-a350|boeing-787":"The two aircraft that finally made the four-engine airliner extinct. Both are majority-composite, both are twins, both fly further on less fuel than anything before them. The A350 is the bigger machine — longer, wider, heavier, more seats — and it exists specifically to answer the 787. The 787 got there first, and in this industry being first is worth a very great deal.","boeing-777|boeing-787":"Same manufacturer, same job description, twenty years apart. The 777 is bigger in every dimension and carries far more people; the 787 flies nearly as far on dramatically less fuel and opened routes too thin for a 777 to ever fill. It is the clearest illustration on this site of what composites and modern engines actually bought aviation — not more speed, not more size, but more range per seat.","antonov-an-225|lockheed-c-5-galaxy":"The only two aircraft ever built to swallow cargo nothing else could take. The An-225 was a one-off, built to carry the Buran space shuttle on its back, and it remains the heaviest aircraft ever flown — 640 tonnes against the Galaxy's 381. It was destroyed in 2022. The C-5 is less romantic, vastly more numerous, and still flying.","concorde|tupolev-tu-144":"The Tu-144 flew first, by two months, and that was rather the entire point of it. It was also faster on paper and worse in almost every way that mattered: it needed afterburners just to hold cruise, it was so loud inside that passengers passed notes, and it carried fare-paying passengers for a grand total of 55 flights. Concorde flew commercially for 27 years. Being first is not the same as being right.","airbus-a330|boeing-787":"The most instructive fight in the widebody market, because it pits a 1992 aluminium airframe against a 2009 composite one — and the old aircraft is still selling. The 787 flies significantly further and burns less fuel. The A330neo costs considerably less to buy, and for a great many routes that is the only number that wins.","boeing-747|boeing-777":"Boeing's own succession, and a quiet act of self-destruction. The 747 is longer, taller, and has the upper deck; the 777 hauls a comparable load on two engines instead of four, which is the whole story. The 777-300ER never beat the 747 on a spec sheet — it beat it on the fuel bill, and that was enough to end the four-engine era at the company that invented it.","airbus-a380|antonov-an-225":"The two heaviest aircraft that ever flew, built for opposite reasons. The An-225 is longer and heavier and lifts more; the A380 has the greater wingspan, a genuine second deck, and has carried over 850 people at once. One was built a single time for a space programme. The other was built 251 times for a market that never arrived.","boeing-737|boeing-757":"The 757 is the aircraft Boeing cannot replace, and this comparison shows why. It is substantially longer than any 737, but its real advantage never appears on a spec table: enormous wing area and oversized engines, which let it climb out of short, hot, high-altitude runways and still cross the Atlantic afterwards. The 737 MAX 10 and the A321XLR are both, in their different ways, attempts to rebuild it.","boeing-767|boeing-787":"The 767 pioneered ETOPS and made the twin-engine ocean crossing legal; the 787 was built to replace it and does nearly everything better. The interesting part is that the 767 refuses to die — it is still in production as a freighter, because a 1981 aluminium fuselage is cheap, simple and perfectly adequate for carrying boxes that do not complain about the cabin.","boeing-b-52|tupolev-tu-160":"The subsonic and the supersonic answers to the same question. The B-52 is a 1952 design that will fly into the 2050s — eight engines, no supersonic pretensions, a bomb truck that has outlived every single aircraft designed to replace it. The Tu-160 is the heaviest and fastest combat aircraft ever built, a Mach 2 swing-wing with nearly twice the weight. One is still in production. The other has simply refused to stop.","boeing-c-17|lockheed-c-5-galaxy":"The strategic airlifter versus the tactical one. The C-5 is far larger and can carry the C-17's payload and then some — but it needs a proper runway to do it. The C-17 is the compromise that actually gets used: less capacity, but it can put 77 tonnes onto a short unpaved strip and then reverse itself back out. Capability on paper against capability where the war actually is.","airbus-a220|embraer-e-jet-e2":"The two aircraft fighting over the 100–150 seat gap that Boeing and Airbus abandoned — the market that cost Bombardier so much that it handed the A220 to Airbus for a single dollar. The A220 is bigger, flies further and has a genuinely wide cabin for its class. The E2 is lighter, cheaper to run and easier to fill. Both are dramatically better than the regional jets they replace.","airbus-a350|boeing-777x":"The current heavyweight bout, and the one that decides widebody flying into the 2040s. The 777-9 is the largest twin ever built — longer than a 747 — with a folding wingtip so that it can still use an ordinary airport gate. The A350-1000 is smaller, lighter, certified and already in service. Boeing's aircraft is more capable and years late; Airbus's is flying and taking the orders.","lockheed-l-1011|mcdonnell-douglas-md-11":"Two trijets, a decade apart, killed by the same thing. The L-1011 was the more advanced aeroplane — it could land itself in 1972 — and Lockheed lost so much money building it that it left the airliner business forever. The MD-11 flew faster and further and still missed its own range promises, and by the time the fixes worked, ETOPS had made the third engine pointless.","boeing-777x|concorde":"The most brutal comparison on this site. In 1976, Concorde crossed the Atlantic at Mach 2.04. In 2026, the newest airliner Boeing can build crosses it at about Mach 0.85 — and the 777X is the better aircraft by almost every commercial measure. It carries four times the passengers, flies twice as far, and does not need a government to subsidise its existence. Aviation did not fail to get faster. It decided not to.","antonov-an-124|lockheed-c-5-galaxy":"The two workhorse outsize freighters of the Cold War, and they are far closer than either side ever cared to admit. The An-124 is longer, spans wider, and lifts more — 150 tonnes against the Galaxy's 122. The C-5 has nose-and-tail loading, which means it can be filled from both ends and turned around faster."};
